  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Improve Resilience &amp; Livelihoods of Extreme Poor HH in Cibitoke &amp; Kirundo Provinces (Pathway out of Poverty (Graduation) Model 2012-2015</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Given the landless status of the extreme poor and the overall land shortage in the Cibitoke and Kirundo Provinces, the core strategy of Concern to lift them out of poverty is to expand the opportunities of casual labourers (Ntahonikora) in non-agricultural economic activities.  With this in mind, the pathway out of poverty (graduation) model was chosen as a key strategy that can increase the extreme poor&#x2019;s ability to take advantage of opportunities and plan for the future. The model consists of 5 essential elements:   1) Targeting                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             2) Consumption                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           3) Savings                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                4) Training and coaching                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         5) Asset Transfer                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    The target households will initially receive consumption support to help them stabilise their consumption levels until they start earning income from the assets that have been enhanced as part of the program, along with practical, hands on skills training and regular coaching/monitoring to ensure they are on track to reach their goals. Asset transfers will then help jump-start a sustainable economic activity and allow beneficiaries to start saving once they have reached a sustainable profit margin. These savings will help the extreme poor manage risks, build resilience and reduce the likelihood of having to sell assets when faced with a shock. Coupled with a lack of access to productive land the extreme poor suffer from a lack of access to medical care, nutrition and education which hinders their physical and psychological functioning. The inability to access key social services and public goods is a factor that inhibits the extremely poor from lifting themselves out of poverty.  For the extreme poor who are unable to work (Aboro), social protection is key to guaranteeing their access to community welfare support (health services, consumption support, etc.).</narrative>
  </description>
